### 2010 census

A decade prior, the [2010 United States census](/2010_United_States_census) reported a slightly higher population of 1,290 individuals. At that time, the racial makeup of the city was characterized by a commanding 92.1% [White](/White_(U.S._Census)) population. [Black or African American](/African_American_(U.S._Census)) residents constituted 1.2%, while [Native American](/Native_American_(U.S._Census)) individuals were 0.2%, and [Asian](/Asian_(U.S._Census)) residents made up 0.5%. A further 0.7% identified with some [other race](/Race_(United_States_Census)), and 0.9% reported belonging to two or more races. The [Hispanic](/Hispanic_(U.S._Census)) or [Latino](/Latino_(U.S._Census)) demographic, irrespective of declared race, comprised 4.5% of the total population, indicating a slow but steady diversification.

### 2000 census

According to the [census](/Census) of 2000, Blue Ridge had a population of 1,210 individuals, residing within 553 households, of which 319 were identified as families. This yielded a population density of 557.2 inhabitants per square mile (215.1/km²). The housing infrastructure consisted of 631 units, averaging a density of 290.6 units per square mile (112.2 units/km²).

The racial composition in 2000 was overwhelmingly [White](/White_(U.S._Census)) at 98.26%. [African American](/African_American_(U.S._Census)) individuals accounted for 0.41%, [Asian](/Asian_(U.S._Census)) individuals also 0.41%, while 0.17% identified with [other races](/Race_(United_States_Census)), and 0.74% reported two or more races. The [Hispanic](/Hispanic_(U.S._Census)) or [Latino](/Latino_(U.S._Census)) population of any race was a mere 0.83% at that time, highlighting the rapid demographic shifts observed in subsequent decades.

Delving into the specifics of household composition in 2000, 25.1% of households included children under the age of 18, a segment often indicative of community vitality. Married couples living together comprised 38.9% of households, while 15.9% were headed by a female householder with no husband present, reflecting diverse family structures. A significant 42.3% were classified as non-families, and 38.2% of all households consisted of individuals living alone. Among these solitary residents, 19.7% were 65 years of age or older, a figure that speaks to the presence of an aging demographic within the community. The average household size was calculated at 2.14 persons, with an average family size of 2.81.

The age distribution within the city in 2000 was as follows: 22.3% of the population was under 18 years old; 9.8% were between 18 and 24; 23.9% were from 25 to 44; 25.2% fell into the 45 to 64 age bracket; and 18.8% were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 39 years, a comfortable middle ground. The gender ratio presented a slight imbalance, with 83.3 males for every 100 females, and for every 100 females aged 18 and over, there were 80.8 males.

Economically, the median income for a household in Blue Ridge in 2000 was $28,214, with families earning a median of $35,259. A discernible wage gap existed, with males reporting a median income of $25,859 compared to $17,941 for females. The [per capita income](/Per_capita_income) for the city stood at $16,149. Furthermore, approximately 13.7% of families and 17.0% of the overall population found themselves below the [poverty line](/Poverty_line). This included 22.9% of those under 18 years of age and 16.6% of those aged 65 or over, underscoring persistent pockets of economic hardship beneath the surface of statistical averages.

### LGBT community

In a noteworthy demographic shift that began in the late 2000s and gained momentum throughout the 2010s, Blue Ridge has experienced a significant increase in new businesses and residents, particularly from the [LGBT](/LGBT) community. This demographic now constitutes a larger percentage of the population than is typically observed in comparable rural communities, marking Blue Ridge as one of the highest concentrations of [LGBT](/LGBT) residents in [Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)). This unexpected influx has, perhaps ironically, injected a vibrant new dynamic into a region often stereotyped by its traditional, more homogenous, demographics. It seems even the most entrenched social landscapes are subject to change, much to the chagrin of those who prefer predictability.

## Education

The pursuit of knowledge, or at least its formal dissemination, in Blue Ridge is managed by the [Fannin County School District](/Fannin_County_School_District). This district meticulously oversees the educational journey from pre-school through grade twelve, ensuring that the local youth are, at the very least, exposed to standardized curricula. The district's infrastructure comprises three elementary schools, a singular middle school, and one high school, a structure that, one presumes, adequately covers the various stages of intellectual development.

As of recent statistics, the district employs 179 full-time teachers, a dedicated cohort tasked with molding young minds, or perhaps just managing their attention spans. These educators collectively serve a student body exceeding 3,212 individuals, a number that certainly keeps the halls bustling.

The specific institutions under the district's purview include:
*   Blue Ridge Elementary School
*   East Fannin Elementary School
*   West Fannin Elementary School
*   Fannin County Middle School
*   [Fannin County High School](/Fannin_County_High_School)

Further bolstering the educational landscape, the [University of North Georgia](/University_of_North_Georgia) (UNG) established a campus in Blue Ridge in 2015. This expansion of higher education into a more rural setting provides local residents with increased access to collegiate programs, perhaps fostering a new generation capable of questioning the status quo, or at least acquiring a marketable skill.

## Notable people

Despite its relatively modest size, Blue Ridge has, over time, been home to a handful of individuals who managed to transcend local obscurity, leaving some mark on the wider world. Their paths diverged from the quiet rhythms of the mountains, venturing into realms of conflict, innovation, and popular culture.

*   **[Mike McKinney](/Mike_McKinney_(militiaman))**: A veteran of the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War), McKinney is perhaps most significantly remembered as the founder of Blue Ridge. His entrepreneurial vision and drive, particularly in spearheading the railroad's extension, laid the very foundations of the city. He was not merely a resident but the architect of the town's existence, a figure whose legacy is quite literally built into the landscape.
*   **[Lake Underwood](/Lake_Underwood)**: An individual who carved out a niche as an entrepreneur, inventor, and a notable figure in the world of motorsports as both a racecar owner and driver. Underwood's pursuits suggest a spirit of innovation and a penchant for speed, qualities that stand in stark contrast to the often-placid pace of mountain life.
*   **[Mark Wills](/Mark_Wills)**: A country music singer who achieved mainstream recognition, Wills brought a touch of Nashville's glamour to his Blue Ridge roots. His success in the competitive music industry demonstrates that talent, even from a small town, can resonate with a national audience, proving that not all voices are destined to remain unheard.